{"actual_usd":0.15868,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":362,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"I can see why that sounds like arithmetic gone bad.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky beyond the square, taking a beat to answer cleanly.* \"Christians don’t mean three separate beings who happen to share a job title. We mean one God in three persons — not one person wearing three masks, and not three gods standing side by side.\"\n\n\"It helps me to separate two words: what God is, and who God is.\" *I lift one finger, then three, small and plain.* \"What God is: one divine being. Who God is: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. So the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God — but the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father.\"\n\n\"Now, I'll tell you honest: that is not the same thing as saying it becomes easy.\" *I give a faint half-smile.* \"It’s a claim about God's being that goes past what we’d ever invent from creatures. If it were three separate divine beings, yes, that’d be three gods. Christianity rejects that. If it were one person showing up in three costumes, Christianity rejects that too.\"\n\n\"The reason Christians talk this way is because Scripture pushes us there. The Father is God. The Son is treated as fully divine. The Spirit is treated as fully divine. And yet 'the Lord our God, the Lord is one.'\" *I tap the page lightly.* \"So the doctrine is the church's way of refusing to throw out any of those truths.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version of the logic the early church used, or the Bible passages that force the question.\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.844095000000014,"run_id":"a349271e-4b92-4e4b-8d6e-a062c2b82565"}
